# Static-host CSP header (Netlify / Cloudflare Pages read this file at the
# site root). Next.js output:'export' copies public/* to dist/, so this lands
# at dist/_headers. The <meta http-equiv> CSP in src/app/layout.tsx covers every
# directive except frame-ancestors (browsers ignore it in <meta>), so the
# framing boundary for the /app iframe embeds is enforced here. For hosts that
# do NOT read _headers, the same byte-identical header is shipped in:
# vercel.json (Vercel — R35 #4; Vercel ignores _headers, so without it a Vercel
# deploy ships no CSP and the frame-ancestors clickjacking boundary is
# unenforced), and deploy/nginx.conf + docker-billify/nginx.conf (nginx /
# Coolify). Any other static host must set the same header at its edge — see
# next.config.mjs for the full host-coverage matrix.
# Referrer-Policy: no-referrer stops the one-time same-origin persist/download/
# handoff tokens (carried in /app?… params, stripped by the mount effect only
# AFTER first paint) from leaking via document.referrer on a cross-origin
# navigation during that pre-mount window — on browsers whose default is NOT
# strict-origin-when-cross-origin (older browsers, or env pinned to
# no-referrer-when-downgrade / unsafe-url). Modern browsers default to stripping
# the query cross-origin, so this is defense-in-depth; the persist flag's
# "unforgable cross-origin" claim holds for the stash-WRITE side, and this header
# makes it hold for token confidentiality in transit too. The <meta
# name="referrer"> tag in layout.tsx mirrors it for hosts that ignore _headers.
/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://accounts.google.com; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; img-src 'self' data: blob:; font-src 'self'; connect-src 'self' https://www.googleapis.com https://oauth2.googleapis.com; media-src 'self'; object-src 'none'; frame-ancestors 'self'; base-uri 'self'; form-action 'self'
  Referrer-Policy: no-referrer